Tonight saw a "people" public tweet "drug crisis: After the closure of the village AIDS, " a few hours months have read 100,000 + . As an AIDS sufferer, the urge to survive made me want to write something. I don't have a reporter's eye view, but I'm one of more than one million people living with AIDS in China, and I think that's enough.

After the closure of Wuhan, I felt the situation was grim and worried that I didn't have enough medicine, so I begged my father to drive me back to the city at 9 pm on the first day of the New Year. Sure enough, we soon had traffic control in our province. For AIDS patients, in the anti-viral period of treatment once the situation such as leakage will face a great risk of drug resistance, all the previous efforts also means the failure. Coupled with the fact that subsequent drugs may need to be imported if they become resistant, the cost can be prohibitive for many patients. So, if we run out of medicine, it can be fatal for us.

I myself have had two years of depression before choosing antiretroviral treatment, and I have heard too many reports of people taking their own lives after getting positive results. For AIDS patients, they may have been indifferent to life and death, but always can not cross the hurdle is facing society, because discrimination has always been one of the most harmful invisible killer. How do you deal with your parents? How do you deal with your wife and children? What if relatives, friends, and colleagues find out? These problems may not be worth mentioning for other diseases, and may even lead to more sympathy and care. However, for AIDS patients, it is no doubt that they are nailed to the stigma, ready to be severely judged by social discrimination, to live a life of moral bondage. If it were just me who had to bear all the pain, but the thought that even death might involve my family, that they would have to be misunderstood and alienated by their surroundings, it would be difficult to die, all that's left is the endless running and covering up.

Anyone infected with HIV who has received anti-viral treatment has actually experienced a death. The medicine is a very, very high bar. It means that you have to put on a mask and face the world with a smile. You have learned that the medicine will not only save your life, but also save the face of the people you care about. I believe that even those who are discriminated against as immoral, immoral and shameless have a long-night confession of "a man's dying words are good" , and the hard time of psychological reconstruction is like the darkest box, lonely only to hear the beating of the heart, tears also dry up in vain, this is how desperate Ah! Those who were able to pass through this barrier experienced a death, and they were willing to believe that what Shi Tiesheng said was an empty space ahead, with nothing but hope, but there is no alternative to accepting the possibility of a second death, a third death... drug resistance, denial, Opportunistic infection, and so on, but we have no choice but to wade through the river of time and then try to make money, for family, for family, for family! I think although we will never be worthy of the struggle in the disease "great" word, but if you can die in the unknown is the mercy of God and the world of love it.

In an article I wrote about my experiences with infections, I had to change my family's residence in order to get my medicine. I had to travel thousands of miles to get a doctor's appointment in order to escape from my hometown, which was supposed to be the most humane place. Like most patients, I did not even dare to use the unit's health insurance to AIDS designated hospitals to use, for fear of revealing that I am an AIDS patient information. The stigmatization of AIDS is still serious today, once we expose the personal situation, not only discrimination, with the serious impact on life and work is very terrible. For us, the biggest fear is getting sick, the kind of sick that needs surgery, the kind of sick that needs a physical. Once I had a fever and went to a community hospital run by a friend of a relative to get an infusion. I thought that the procedure in a small hospital was simple and that a few bottles of water would be OK. I avoided the fear of various examinations in a large hospital. I did not expect to have a blood test there, it scared the hell out of me, because if there was a test for quadriplegics, I'd be exposed, and my relatives would know. Scared, I asked the doctor about the procedure and was relieved to learn that it was just a blood test. Think about it, even the right to be sick do not dare to have, that is a kind of sad?

Wuhan pneumonia caused by AIDS patients with drug panic, I would like to say that the most fundamental reason is that the current situation may expose the privacy of anti-virus treatment. I once wrote in my diary that I had finally turned my life into a grand plan. In fact, every person with AIDS from the day they decide to get their medicine has already begun to plan for the rest of their lives, and how to keep their identity as secret as possible is their primary consideration, so there is a private path for everyone to take medicine and take it. The current road closure is no doubt intended to break the path they had originally set for survival. It is conceivable that it will not be as simple as asking for a pass and then temporarily getting medicine, especially for people living with AIDS in rural areas, how do I state my reasons for leaving the village? Who doesn't know who in a village? Maybe that's the last Straw. As the number of drugs in the medicine cabinet dwindles, anxiety, confusion, and fear come over me, locking not only my feet, but the terrible consequences of drug resistance and the fear of exposure, brought more despair than pneumonia. The secret life they have built, the choice between life and death, the choice between life and death, the choice between life and death, the choice between life and death, the choice between life and death? It may be difficult for non-sensitive people to understand this emotion, and even think of making a mountain out of a molehill, think too much, but I would like to say that this is the truth, this is the feeling of many people with AIDS.

We are vulnerable people, but rather than experiencing the death of AIDS, we are not afraid, only hope to live with dignity and dignity. There's no turning back, but I have to go back, because responsibility and responsibility, I don't live alone. So, please, give me the medicine.
